			<div class="content" id="post-content-1867865">
									

<p>Long shot, but here's my best guess:</p>
<p>The amulet on the Indian man in the waste compartment is the root cause of the June 1987 anomaly. Somehow, it allows (or at least allowed) its carrier to manipulate space-time in four dimensions. There is loose thematic ground for this, as the Wadjet Eye in ancient Egypt represented a direct connection to the forces responsible for creating and shaping the universe. This man, working as a hitman for organized crime in California, used (rather, will use, as this must take place at some point in the future) the amulet to facilitate accurate travel and escape via the use of warping space to create wormholes.</p>
<p>At some point, this man was hired to kill someone on board a plane, mid-flight. Instead of stowing away on the plane, he attempted to use the amulet to &quot;warp&quot; aboard the flight mid-air. However, at the same time he attempted to create a wormhole, the flight was rocked by turbulence, and the point of arrival was moved into the waste compartment. Panicking, he attempted to immediately create a second wormhole to escape the compartment, which resulted in a massive spatial anomaly which engulfed the entire airplane, sucking it into a wormhole.</p>
<p>Because it was incomplete, the other end of the hole closed before the transit was finished, and the plane experienced a temporal collapse, compressing all time that would have been experienced by objects within the plane into an instant. This had the immediate effect of replacing all humans on board with their corpses at the time of their deaths from various point in the &quot;future.&quot; In addition, as the plane was now outside the known universe, reality contained within the plane began to decay, with numerous bizarre results detailed in the article.</p>
<p>After some &quot;time,&quot; the plane reentered the known universe, manifesting itself in what we would call its &quot;past&quot; at its resting place in Washington State in June, 1987. Reality within the craft remains permanently altered and occasional anomalous breaches reflect this, which is why it violently repels fully &quot;real&quot; sentient observers for a time period following these events; perhaps the corrupted reality fundamentally repels the normal version as a defense mechanism against creating a paradox.</p>
<p>I'm sure the physics are BS, and it doesn't explain everything, but this could be a reasonable hypothesis for explaining:</p>
<ul>
<li>Why there was a guy in the waste compartment</li>
<li>Why he had a shotgun</li>
<li>Why he had an odd Egyptian pendant</li>
<li>Why everyone on board is dead in a seemingly unrelated variety of ways</li>
<li>Why, in general, events that take place on board are bizarre but consistently composed of recognizable elements</li>
<li>Why people are repelled for a time period following an event on the airplane</li>
<li>Why the optometrist from Georgia claims never to have been on a plane, as his plane ride takes place at some point in the future</li>
</ul>
<p>Upvoted, by the way.</p>

